V\u000a\u000a\u201cThe sun is God,\u201d were the last words uttered by Joseph Mallord William Turner on Dec. 19, 1851.
p684
tp685
a(I0
VNow proclaimed as Britain\u2019s greatest artist, his talent is the soul of Mike Leigh\u2018s new film, Mr. Turner.
p686
tp687
a(I0
VComing after his other historical dramas\u2014the effervescent Topsy-Turvy, about Gilbert and Sullivan, and the dreary, bleak Vera Drake, which focuses on an abortionist in the 1950s\u2014this is perhaps his most spare, yet illuminating film to date.
p688
tp689
a(I0
VHe\u2019s certainly picked a perfect subject: Turner was a bona fide genius who never stopped experimenting or challenging convention, yet, as Leigh shows, his personal life was a mess, including unhappy illegitimate children and a rather odd housekeeper who provided à la carte services for her boss.
p690
tp691
a(I0
VThough Leigh\u2019s film follows a basic chronological approach, starting when the artist is at the height of his fame, it is arranged as a series of vignettes rather than a completely fleshed out, plot-driven movie.
p692
tp693
a(I0
VAnd for someone as complex as J.M.W.
p694
tp695
a(I0
VTurner, that is perhaps the best way to capture the dichotomy of the man.
p696
tp697
a(I0
VCoddled by his father, who runs his household, sells his paintings and even mixes the valuable pigments and colours used to create those spectacular works of art, Turner is a crude, driven man comfortable in his selfishness.
p698
tp699
a(I0
VHis world revolves around his ability to translate three-dimensional vistas into two-dimensional paintings.
p700
tp701
a(I0
VHe thinks nothing of dropping everything, and everyone, for a painting excursion.
p702
tp703
a(I0
VIt\u2019s actor Timothy Spall who brings what could have been a two-dimensional caricature to life.
p704
tp705
a(I0
VSpall immersed himself in the Dickensian world of Victorian London, even spending two years learning to paint.
p706
tp707
a(I0
